[3] Cholera ex Philippines & Typhoid - Taiwan
Date: Wed, 28 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Taipei Times [edited]
<http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/front/archives/2004/07/28/2003180729>

Typhus [typhoid?], cholera pose `no danger'
----------------------------------
1 case of cholera and 3 cases of typhus [based on the description
below, this is probably abdominal typhus, also more commonly referred
to as typhoid - Mod.LL] uncovered on Mon, 26 Jul 2004, in the
nation's south are being monitored but pose no danger to public
health, the Center for Disease Control said on Tue, 27 Jul 2004.
The center confirmed that 3 workers at a factory manufacturing
soy-bean sauce and ketchup in Pingtung County have been infected with
[typhoid] since early this month, Jul 2004, but were recovering in
hospital. The source of the infection remained uncertain, though it
was reported that the 3 patients had not been overseas.
The 13 other employees at the factory and the 3 patients' families
have also been cleared of infection. Officials yesterday said that
quarantine measures would be imposed on all parties until 20 Aug
2004. Wu Ping-fuai, director of the center's Division of Quarantine
and Intervention Activities, told the Taipei Times that the situation
is under control. About 30 cases of [typhoid] occur in Taiwan every
year. "Due to the lengthy incubation period of [typhoid], which is
2-4 weeks, the sources are difficult to confirm," Wu said. After
obtaining 3 negative test results, the patients will be declared
disease-free.
Food products manufactured at the factory prior to 15 Jun 2004 have
been tested by the Department of Health. Officials said that results
would be released by the next few days. "The situation is under
control because the [typhoid] did not occur in local communities," Wu
said.
Meanwhile, the department announced that a Taiwanese man who
contracted cholera in Manila remains hospitalized in Kaohsiung. It
the 1st case of cholera contracted overseas this year. The man is
reported to have eaten grilled seafood on Mon, 19 Jul 2004. The next
day, he suffered from acute diarrhea. The man reported his symptoms
when he returned to the country 21 Jul 2004. A diagnosis of cholera
was confirmed after an examination.
[Byline: Chiu Yu-Tzu]
