[4] Diarrhea - Bangladesh
Date: Wed, 28 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Daily Star [edited]
<http://www.thedailystar.net/2004/07/28/d407282502126.htm>

Hospitals fill with diarrhea patients
-------------------------------------
The diarrhea outbreak has taken a serious turn in flood-hit areas,
and experts fear the worst will come when the floodwaters recede.
Sources at the International Centre for Diarrhea Diseases Research,
Bangladesh (ICDDR,B), popularly known as Mohakhali Cholera Hospital,
said 475 patients, most of them children, were admitted to the center
yesterday, Tue, 27 Jul 2004. On the previous day, the number was 441.
They said the number of diarrhea patients are increasing every day.
"This is already serious, but the diarrhea outbreak will peak in the
form of an epidemic as floodwaters recede," said Dr PK Bardhan, a
scientist at the ICDDR,B. He also said that an adequate supply of
pure drinking water in the affected areas is now urgently needed to
arrest spread of the waterborne disease.
The ICDDR,B has taken all preparations to handle the expected
increase of patients in the coming days. "We handled more than 900
patients a day during the 1998 flood. We are now capable of handling
even more patients if need be" said Ramzan Ali, hospital manager of
the ICDDR,B.
Most patients coming to the ICDDR'B for treatment are from
Rayerbazar, Khilgaon, Bashabo, Badda Kuril, Demra, Beraid, Malibagh,
Shantibagh, Mohammadpur and Keranigonj. Shishu Hospital also reported
a 15-20 percent increase in diarrhoea patients this week compared to
last week.
The hospital authorities also said they have made every preparation
to face the post-flood attack of diarrhea and other related diseases.
The flood shelters are hit hard by the disease because of a dearth of
drinking water. Hospitals and clinics are flooding with an increased
number of diarrhea patients every day. The situation has turned even
worse as sewerage water has [become backed up] over almost 1/3 of the
city, escaping into water pipelines and reservoirs. Although Water and
[Though the] Sewerage Authority (Wasa) has been supplying drinking
water through its mobile teams at 14 points, the effort is inadequate
to serve the large number of people affected in 56 wards. As a result
many flood-hit people are compelled to drink contaminated water.
[Byline: Kausar Islam Ayon]
