[5] Cholera - Pakistan (Nawab Shah)
Date: Wed, 28 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Paktribune.com [edited]
<http://www.paktribune.com/news/index.php?id=72191>

Cholera claims 4 lives in Nawab Shah
----------------------------------------
At least 4 children were killed by the cholera epidemic in various
areas of Nawab Shah.
Tehsil Daulatpur and Shahpur Jehanian are amongst the most affected
areas, where a 2-year-old, a 3-year-old, a 1-year-old and a
1-1/2-year-old infant became victims of the deadly disease.
[Residents] lamented that no medicine to cure the patients was
available at local hospitals and medical centres and that not a
single medical team was sent to the area to ascertain the damage
caused by the disease.
*****
[6] Cholera - Chad
Date: Thu, 29 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: IOL (Independent Online) website [edited]
<http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=68&art_id=qw1091110502536B232>

Cholera downs dozens in Chad
-------------------------------
An outbreak of cholera in Chad has killed 50 people and infected
almost 700 in the Central African state since the beginning of Jun
2004, a health ministry official said on Thu, 29 Jul 2004.
"To date we have registered 696 cases, including 50 deaths," the
official said. "The outbreak is in Ndjamena and the surrounding area
as well as in the Lake Chad and Kanem regions to the west of the
capital."
The previous cholera outbreak in Chad was in 2001, when more than
3500 cases were registered and 113 people died, according to the WHO.
"We're not panicking because we have taken all measures needed by
opening an equipped centre to take in all those sick with cholera,"
the health ministry's secretary general Hassan Mahamad Hassan told
reporters.
